lic university]] in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].  The [[university]] was created in 1993 and it is located in the city of [[Goma]], near [[Lake Kivu]] in the east of the country.  The rector of the school is Jean-Baptiste Gakura Semacumu.\n\n==External links==\n{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.auf.org/membre.php3?id=509 University of Goma's page at the Agence universitaire de la Francophonie ]\n*[http://www.sarua.org/?q=uni_Universit%C3%A9+de+Goma Southern African University]\n{{coord missing|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Goma]]\n[[Category:Goma]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Zaire]]\n\n{{DRCongo-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Goma"}
{"title_page": "University of Global Health Equity", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo = Logo_for_UGHE.jpg\n| type = Private not-for-profit university\n| leader_title = Vice Chancellor\n| leader_name = [[Agnes Binagwaho]], MD, M(Ped), PhD\n| key_people = [[Paul Farmer]], MD, PhD; Abebe Bekele, MD, FCS; Hellen Amuguni, DVM, MA, PhD\n| affiliations = Cummings Foundation, Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, [[Harvard Medical School]], [[Tufts University]], Government of Rwanda\n| founded = 2015\n| location = [[Rwanda]], Africa\n| website = [http://ughe.org/ ughe.org]\n}}\n\n'''University of Global Health Equity''' (UGHE) is a health sciences university in Rwanda. An initiative of [[Partners In Health]], UGHE is a private, not-for-profit, accredited institution.\n\nCatalytic partners that have helped to launch the University include: Cummings Foundation, [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]], and the Government of Rwanda. The Cummings Foundation committed an initial $15 million for Phase I of the University and was instrumental in raising matching funds from other sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://woburn.wickedlocal.com/news/20161003/cummings-foundation-hosts-rwandan-university-executive-director|title=Cummings Foundation hosts Rwandan university executive director|work=Woburn Advocate|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 2013, the Government of Rwanda and Partners In Health were considering building a medical school next to [[Butaro Hospital]]. At that same time, Joyce and Bill Cummings, founders of the Cummings Foundation in [[Woburn, Massachusetts]], visited [[Rwanda]] for the ribbon-cutting of the Butaro Outpatient Cancer Infusion Center, whose construction had been funded by the Cummings Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philanthropy.texterity.com/philanthropy/20140508?pg=11#pg11|title=The Chronicle of Philanthropy - May 08, 2014 - 11|website=philanthropy.texterity.com|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> During their visit, the Cummings shared an expanded vision for the proposed medical school that would be \"pan-African\" and would include multiple health science disciplines, including veterinary medicine, dentistry and nursing.\n\nPaul Farmer responded to this idea by writing in an email, \"What a great vision, and one that squares with the Rwandan vision of pulling people up by building a \u2018knowledge\u2019 economy while delivering care.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://woburn.wickedlocal.com/news/20161003/cummings-foundation-hosts-rwandan-university-executive-director|title=Cummings Foundation hosts Rwandan university executive director|work=Woburn Advocate|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLaunched in September 2015,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/paul-farmer-s-lifelong-dream-86915|title=Paul Farmer's 'lifelong dream'|date=2015-09-17|work=Devex|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref> UGHE is a new kind of university focused on delivering the highest quality of health care by addressing the critical social and systemic forces causing inequities and inefficiencies in health care delivery.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-07-01|title=Medical Education and Global Health Equity|url=http://journalofethics.ama-assn.org/2016/07/medu1-1607.html|journal=AMA Journal of Ethics|volume=18|issue=7|pages=702\u2013709|doi=10.1001/journalofethics.2016.18.7.medu1-1607|pmid=27437820 | last1 = Drobac | first1 = P | last2 = Morse | first2 = M}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\nOn April 3, 2017, UGHE appointed former Minister of Health of Rwanda, [[Agnes Binagwaho]], MD, M(Ped), PhD, as Vice Chancellor of the University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnbcafrica.com/videos/2017/04/06/ex-rwandan-minister-of-health-to-lead-partners-in-health-university/|title=Ex-Rwandan minister of health to lead Partners in Health University - CNBC Africa|date=2017-04-06|work=CNBC Africa|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/a-call-for-implementation-science-and-systems-innovation-in-global-health-89872|title=A call for implementation science and systems innovation in global health|date=2017-04-25|work=Devex|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref> As Vice Chancellor of UGHE, Professor Binagwaho oversees the expansion of the University\u2019s education and research programs, cultivation of global partnerships, and further development of its Butaro campus in northern Rwanda.\n\n=== Master of Science in Global Health Delivery ===\nLaunched in September 2015, the Master of Science in Global Health Delivery (MGHD) is UGHE\u2019s flagship academic program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ughe.org/academics/mghd/|title=Master of Science in Global Health Delivery - UGHE|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=UGHE|access-date=2016-10-14|url-status=live|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery ===\nUGHE\u2019s joint Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery/Master of Science in Global Health Delivery (MBBS/MGHD) is a six and a half-year, bachelor\u2019s level medical degree coupled with a master\u2019s level global health degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ughe.org/academics/bachelor-medicine-bachelor-surgery/|title=Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|website=UGHE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Executive Education ===\nUGHE\u2019s Executive Education certificate courses develop professionals using critical competencies central to strengthening health care delivery systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ughe.org/academics/executive-education/|title=Executive Education|website=UGHE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Campus Development ==\nIn 2016, UGHE began construction on its first permanent campus in Butaro, Rwanda. Completed in January 2019, the campus was inaugurated by the President of Rwanda, Paul Kagame.  The university houses classrooms, teaching laboratories, a clinical simulation center, and information commons, as well as administrative, dining, and lodging facilities for staff, students, and faculty. As the university grows, a second campus will be added in Kigali at Masaka.\n\nThe university is composed of complementary rural and urban campuses. In December 2016, UGHE began construction on the 250-acre Butaro academic campus, which is embedded in a rural primary health care delivery system. The first phase of the campus opened in 2018 with classrooms, administrative buildings, a library, and dorms. The urban campus will be located in Masaka Sector, Kicukiro District in the Rwandan capital of [[Kigali]], the heart of a planned \u201cmedical city\u201d. In addition to leveraging two existing clinical facilities \u2013 [[Butaro Hospital]] and [[Masaka Hospital, Rwanda|Masaka Hospital]] in Kigali \u2013 UGHE will utilize PIH-supported sites across Rwanda to enable a breadth of educational opportunities in clinical and delivery settings. These campuses were designed by MASS Design and [[Shepley Bulfinch]], one of the oldest architecture firms in continuous practice in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://massdesigngroup.org/work/design/university-global-health-equity|title=University of Global Health Equity {{!}} MASS Design Group|website=massdesigngroup.org|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Rwanda}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Rwanda]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2015]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Rwanda]]\n[[Category:Education in Rwanda]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo = Logo_for_UGHE.jpg\n| type = Private not-for-profit university\n| leader_title = Vice Chancellor\n| leader_name = [[Agnes Binagwaho]], MD, M(Ped), PhD\n| key_people = [[Paul Farmer]], MD, PhD; Abebe Bekele, MD, FCS; Hellen Amuguni, DVM, MA, PhD\n| affiliations = Cummings Foundation, Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, [[Harvard Medical School]], [[Tufts University]], Government of Rwanda\n| founded = 2015\n| location = [[Rwanda]], Africa\n| website = [http://ughe.org/ ughe.org]\n}}\n\n'''University of Global Health Equity''' (UGHE) is a health sciences university in Rwanda. An initiative of [[Partners In Health]], UGHE is a private, not-for-profit, accredited institution.\n\nCatalytic partners that have helped to launch the University include: Cummings Foundation, [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]], and the Government of Rwanda. The Cummings Foundation committed an initial $15 million for Phase I of the University and was instrumental in raising matching funds from other sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://woburn.wickedlocal.com/news/20161003/cummings-foundation-hosts-rwandan-university-executive-director|title=Cummings Foundation hosts Rwandan university executive director|work=Woburn Advocate|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 2013, the Government of Rwanda and Partners In Health were considering building a medical school next to [[Butaro Hospital]]. At that same time, Joyce and Bill Cummings, founders of the Cummings Foundation in [[Woburn, Massachusetts]], visited [[Rwanda]] for the ribbon-cutting of the Butaro Outpatient Cancer Infusion Center, whose construction had been funded by the Cummings Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philanthropy.texterity.com/philanthropy/20140508?pg=11#pg11|title=The Chronicle of Philanthropy - May 08, 2014 - 11|website=philanthropy.texterity.com|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> During their visit, the Cummings shared an expanded vision for the proposed medical school that would be \"pan-African\" and would include multiple health science disciplines, including veterinary medicine, dentistry and nursing.\n\nPaul Farmer responded to this idea by writing in an email, \"What a great vision, and one that squares with the Rwandan vision of pulling people up by building a \u2018knowledge\u2019 economy while delivering care.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://woburn.wickedlocal.com/news/20161003/cummings-foundation-hosts-rwandan-university-executive-director|title=Cummings Foundation hosts Rwandan university executive director|work=Woburn Advocate|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLaunched in September 2015,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/paul-farmer-s-lifelong-dream-86915|title=Paul Farmer's 'lifelong dream'|date=2015-09-17|work=Devex|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref> UGHE is a new kind of university focused on delivering the highest quality of health care by addressing the critical social and systemic forces causing inequities and inefficiencies in health care delivery.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-07-01|title=Medical Education and Global Health Equity|url=http://journalofethics.ama-assn.org/2016/07/medu1-1607.html|journal=AMA Journal of Ethics|volume=18|issue=7|pages=702\u2013709|doi=10.1001/journalofethics.2016.18.7.medu1-1607|pmid=27437820 | last1 = Drobac | first1 = P | last2 = Morse | first2 = M}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\nOn April 3, 2017, UGHE appointed former Minister of Health of Rwanda, [[Agnes Binagwaho]], MD, M(Ped), PhD, as Vice Chancellor of the University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnbcafrica.com/videos/2017/04/06/ex-rwandan-minister-of-health-to-lead-partners-in-health-university/|title=Ex-Rwandan minister of health to lead Partners in Health University - CNBC Africa|date=2017-04-06|work=CNBC Africa|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/a-call-for-implementation-science-and-systems-innovation-in-global-health-89872|title=A call for implementation science and systems innovation in global health|date=2017-04-25|work=Devex|access-date=2017-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref> As Vice Chancellor of UGHE, Professor Binagwaho oversees the expansion of the University\u2019s education and research programs, cultivation of global partnerships, and further development of its Butaro campus in northern Rwanda.\n\n=== Master of Science in Global Health Delivery ===\nLaunched in September 2015, the Master of Science in Global Health Delivery (MGHD) is UGHE\u2019s flagship academic program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ughe.org/academics/mghd/|title=Master of Science in Global Health Delivery - UGHE|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=UGHE|access-date=2016-10-14|url-status=live|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== '''Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery''' ===\nUGHE\u2019s joint Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery/Master of Science in Global Health Delivery (MBBS/MGHD) is a six and a half-year, bachelor\u2019s level medical degree coupled with a master\u2019s level global health degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ughe.org/academics/bachelor-medicine-bachelor-surgery/|title=Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|website=UGHE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> \n\n=== Executive Education ===\nUGHE\u2019s Executive Education certificate courses develop professionals using critical competencies central to strengthening health care delivery systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ughe.org/academics/executive-education/|title=Executive Education|website=UGHE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Campus Development ==\nIn 2016, UGHE began construction on its first permanent campus in Butaro, Rwanda. Completed in January 2019, the campus was inaugurated by the President of Rwanda, Paul Kagame.  The university houses classrooms, teaching laboratories, a clinical simulation center, and information commons, as well as administrative, dining, and lodging facilities for staff, students, and faculty. As the university grows, a second campus will be added in Kigali at Masaka.\n\nThe university is composed of complementary rural and urban campuses. In December 2016, UGHE began construction on the 250-acre Butaro academic campus, which is embedded in a rural primary health care delivery system. The first phase of the campus opened in 2018 with classrooms, administrative buildings, a library, and dorms. The urban campus will be located in Masaka Sector, Kicukiro District in the Rwandan capital of [[Kigali]], the heart of a planned \u201cmedical city\u201d. In addition to leveraging two existing clinical facilities \u2013 [[Butaro Hospital]] and [[Masaka Hospital, Rwanda|Masaka Hospital]] in Kigali \u2013 UGHE will utilize PIH-supported sites across Rwanda to enable a breadth of educational opportunities in clinical and delivery settings. These campuses were designed by MASS Design and [[Shepley Bulfinch]], one of the oldest architecture firms in continuous practice in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://massdesigngroup.org/work/design/university-global-health-equity|title=University of Global Health Equity {{!}} MASS Design Group|website=massdesigngroup.org|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Rwanda}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Rwanda]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2015]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Rwanda]]\n[[Category:Education in Rwanda]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Global_Health_Equity"}
